{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_kale_ver01/data/2017236974/00279558078/1945083001/0774.xml":{"full_text":"Cottons Offer Answer To\nSummer-Into-Fall Season\nThe transition from summer in\nto fall is always a clothes prob\nlem and too often it means an\nuncomfortable period in new\ndresses and suits that were meant\nfor really cold weather\u2014not the\nIndian Summer days that predom\ninate in September, October, and,\nin the South, November. A natural\nsolution is comfortable cotton\ndresses of plaid gingham, solid\ncolor chantbray, and checked suit\ning that are equally at ease in the\nclass-room or office.\nBoth business girls and college\nstudents are considering careful\nly what clothes will take them\nthrough a productive year with\nthe least expense. Dark cotton\ndirndls are a \u201cmust\u201d for the miss\nwith economy in mind, for they\ncan be worn with a whole ward\nrobe of cotton blouses. Some\nskirts come with inset bands of\nwhite cotton eyelet which makes\nthem perfect companions to sheer\nbatiste drop-shoulder blouses that\nare booked for party wear this\nfall. Shirttails are tucked neat\nly out of sight under slim skirts\nthis year. Jackets are boxy, dis\ntinguished by Chinese collars and\ni i__ rpu _ frnnf\nliaicu\ncardigan is still holding its own\nin sports types with contrasting\nbinding; in dressy styles with\nbraid trims.\nNot content with having stolen\nthe shirts off men\u2019s backs, includ\ning their nightshirts, college girls\nthis semester, according to the\nCotton Textile Institute and the\nNational Cotton Council, are tak\ning the \u201cfatigue pants\u201d and \u201cpilot\ncoats\u201d worn by servicemen. The\npilot coats come in red or nat\nural in water-repellent cotton\ngabardine or poplin with fleece\nlining and lapels of deep, cotton\nbacked pile.\nAnother college item which can\nKiwanians\nAnnounce 9\nFuture Plans\nSeeking to speed reconversion\nand aid returning veterans,\nKiwanis International today an\nnounced nine far-reaching post\nwar objectives as the Kiwanis\nClub of Roanoke Rapids considered\nways and means of rendering\ngreater community service in\npeacetime.\nIn a special message to 2,300\nclubs throughout the United States\nand Canada, Hamilton Holt, Ma\ncon, Ga., president of Kiwanis In\nternational, declared that 149,000\nKiwanians \u201cwill not shrink from\nthe problems of reconversion that\nlie ahead.\u201d\nHolt told President Truman and\nPrime Minister King of Canada in\ntelegrams read to the local club\nthat Kiwanis International would\nlend its wholehearted cooperation\nin meeting and solving the prob\nlems of post-war reconstruction.\n\"Since Dunkirk and Pearl Har\nbor,\u201d he said, \u201cKiwanis- manpower\nhas been marshalled behind the\nallied war effort. These resources\nnow will be directed toward the\nhuilding- of Deace. unity and op\nportunity.\u201d\nJ. B. Dunn, president of the\nKiwanis Club of Roanoke Rapids\nsaid that Kiwanis International\u2019s\npost-war objectives had the un\nanimous endorsement of Kiwan\nians here. He revealed that the\nservice organization\u2019s theme would\nbe \u201cBuild for Peace\u2014Unity\u2014Op\nportunity.\u201d\nThe nine objectives follow:\n1. Develop and understanding of\nthe United Nations Charter in sup\nport of world peac^.\n2. Aid returning veterans.\n3. Encourage sound programs of\nreconversion.\n4. Strengthen democracy by per\nsonal acceptance of citizenship re\nsponsibilities.\n5. Expand youth service to build\ncharacter and citizenship.\n6. Mobilize public opinion in sup\nport of individual enterprise and\nopportunity.\n7. Conserve natural resources.\nS. Further good will between\nCanada and the United States as\nbe worn also at home by the bus\niness girl is blue jeans. These\ncame out of the West to be ac\ncepted by the more casual clothes\nlovers all over the country. The\nlumberjacket is revived and re\nvitalized in cotton corduroy with\ndrawstring or elasticized waist\nIt looks well worn with slacks\nor with long shorts for fall\nsports these last for the long\nlegged only. Pedal pushers, less\ncumbersome than slacks, are per\nfect for bicycling, homework ses\nsions and gab fests.\nDate duds are fancy things\nwithout being too extreme. Pep\nlum dresses, bustle-back suits, cap\nsleeve dresses and jumpers,\ndirndl styles will do quite a bit\nof dining out and dancing from\nn_i. _ i_T*\u00ab wirtni- f Viocn\ncotton velveteen has been team\ned happily with wool, turning\nthe cotton fabric shortage into an\nattractive style trend. To the\nearly birds will go the few prized\nall velveteen suits in rich colors,\nbrightened by silver or jet but\ntons, bound with braid. Beau bait\nare the corduroys and wide-wale\nplush suits with drawstring backs\nand peg-top skirts. In these, acqua,\nshocking pink, and gray predomi\nnate.\nIn coats, lovely hollowcut vel\nveteen is a favorite. For dressy\noccasions, the flared back, dolman\nsleeve, three-quarter length style\ndraws the vote. For less formal\noccasions, the greatcoat type with\nyoke details, huge lapels, silver\nbuttons, stand-up collars and\nwide belts is getting a big play.\nWhen the rains come, watch\n\u2018he gay parade of shiny cottor\nraincoats. The girls love them in\nblack and chartreuse, but the\nbeige cotton trench coat is still a\npopular number.\nDEATHS\nA. G. WALTERS\nA. G. Walters, 63, of Greenville,\nN. C., died in Portsmouth, Va., on\nAugust 12 after a short illness.\nFuneral services were conducted\nat his home Wednesday at three\no\u2019clock by Rev. H. G. Haney, pas\ntor of the Eighth Street Christian\nChurch. Interment in the Chury\nHill Cemetery. Mr. Walters was\nborn and reared in Washington\ncounty and went to Greenville in\n1913 where he went into business.\nHe is survived by a son of his\nfirst marriage, Pfc. Raymond Wal\nters of the army; his second wife;\nthree daughters, Mrs. Lester Jones\nand Mrs. Edward Smith, both of\nGreenville; Mrs. Joe Willard of\nAugusta, Ga.; several brothers and\nan outstanding example of inter\nnational cooperation.\n9. Develop national unity through\nincreased emphasis on human and\nj spiritual values.\nFinal Appeal\nWar Fund Be\nMade In Fall\nThe final appeal for the Nat\nional War Fund will be made this\nfall, with the budget set as $115,\n000,000 in order to finance mem\nber agencies to liquidation or for\nfifteen months, through 1946, ac\ncording to advices received today\nby Chairman Victor S. Bryant, of\nDurham.\nMr. Bryant stated that the Nat\nional War Fund had advised him\nthat, with the exception of Ameri\ncan Field Service, V-J Day does\nnot signify an immediate end to\nthe work of member agencies of\nthe Fund.\n\u201cUSO and USO-Camp Shows\nmust carry on their programs for\nour service men until demobiliza\ntion is an actuality,\u201d Mr. Bryant\nsaid. \u201cWhile it is expected that\nthere will be shifts in the areas\nof service and reductions in the\nUSO budget, the work in the Pa\ncific will have to be maintained\nat a high level, and USO-Camp\nShows will face expanded pro\ngrams for men who are in forces\not occupation.\nUnited Seamen\u2019s Service will\nalso have to continue its work\nwhile the merchant fleets are en\ngaged in bringing men and ma\nteriel home, Mr. Bryant said.\nNo immediate change is in sight\nfor the budget of foreign relief\ntgencies which are members of\nhe National War Fund, Mr. Bry\nant continued. He pointed out tha'\nPresident Truman, in his report to\nI he people after his return from\nPotsdam had made it clear that\nthe people of this country have t\nresponsibility to aid the war vie\n.ims of those nations which fought\nwith us.\nPresident Truman said: \u201cEurope\ntoday is hungry As winter\ncomes on the distress will in\ncrease. Unless we do what we can\nto help, we may lose next wintei\nwhat we won at such terrible cost\nlast spring. Desperate men are\nliable to destroy the structure of\ntheir society to find in the\nwreckage some substitute for hope\nWe must help to the limit of\nour strength. And we will.\nIn its appeal this fall, the Nat\nional War Fund will urge the\nAmerican people to \u201cBe Generous\nin Victory.\u2019\u2019\nsisters, Noah G. Walters, H. M\nWalters, Rudolph Walters, Mrs. B\nF. Strickland, Mrs. C. B. Williams\nMrs. M. M. Williams, and a step\nmother, Mrs. W. B. Walters, a!'\nof this city. Lewis Walters and\nJoseph Walters of the army; John\nL. Walters and Mrs. Haywood\nModlin of Jacksonville, and Lloyd\nWalters of Plymouth, and Charlie\nWalters of Scotland Neck and\nMrs. Claude Gayle of Newport\nNews, Va.\nCrowds Swarm Into'Lions\nClub Festival Showgrounds\nRed Cross\nNews Notes\nThe American Red Cross has\nmade plans to make available to\nits very deserving volunteers ser\nvice pins with symbols for the\nnumber of hours served. These\nare for hours served in any phase\nof Red Cross work, surgical dress\nings, production, Home Service,\netc. If you are interested in secur\ning your pin, turn in your name\nand number of hours contributed\nto the chairman of that phase of\nRed Cross work in the chapter or\nto the Red Cross office, R-815-6.\nThe soldiers attached to the\nlocal P. O. W. Camp are trying\nto fix a day room in which they\nmay relax while off duty or when\non the alert. They need comfor\ntable chairs, lamps, books, mag\nazines, tables. Won\u2019t you let us\nknow if you have any of these\narticles which you would care to\ncontribute? With fall houseclean\ning around the corner, you may\nfind this request will help you in\ndiscarding. If you will let us know\nwhat you have and your address,\nwe shall be glad to call for it.\nDuring June, 1945, 25 nurses\u2019\naides served 502 hours in the Roa\nnoke Rapids Hospital. This brings\nthe total hours service rendered\nsince July 1, 1941, to 12,741.\nThe GI patients at a U. S.\nHundreds of people Iiterg|v\nswarmed the Lions Club festmil\nshowgrounds Monday, Tuesday\nand Wednesday nights. The show\nthis year appears on an even keel\nwith that of past seasons, in that\nthere are many entertaining fea\ntures on the midway. Games, of\ncourse, predominate, but apparent\nly they are \u201cclean\u201d and members\nof the local club certainly are\nkeeping a diligent eye on things.\nThe tent shows run about 4he\nsame, but there are several good\nriding features, such as the Mer\nry-go-round, the Ridee-o, ferris\nwheel, plane ride, and the smaller\nplane ride for little children. The\n\u201cred apple,\u201d hot dog and amuse\nment concessions are dome a\nthriving business and judging from\nthe crowds around the different\nplaces it would seem that pre\nwar days are back again, with\nJohn Q. Public casting to Qb\nwinds the thoughts of war and\njoining in the hilarious fun and\nfrolic of days when \u201cwe were\nyoung.\u201d\nProceeds of the week\u2019s festival,\nafter expenses and commissions\nare deducted, go to charity pro\niects sponsored by the Lions Club\nin Roanoke Rapids. The show be\ngins at 8 and is held at Simmons\nball park.\narmy hospital in Germany are\ngetting their recreation in a build\ning formerly used as a photogra\nphic laboratory for the German\nLuftwaffe. Red Cross workers\ncharged with organizing the pro\ngram dragged out stored German\nequipment, which included a hand\ncarved baby grand piano and real\nbeer hall tables.\nI NO COUPONS\nNEEDED\nFUEL OIL KEROSENE\nARE NO LONGER RATIONED.\n\nLet us fill your tank now and avoid the\nWinter Rush.\n\nROANOKE RAPIDS OIL CO.\nI JAKE SPIRE, Mgr.\nI 1314 Roanoke Ave. Phones R-315 and R-568-1\ni ACCLAIM I\n_ 5.90\nI There\u2019s a^feason why Acclaim is a popular style.\nTriple-stitched binding keeps the brim in shape. Cus-\ntom Quality fur felts respond to gentle shaping. Its\nlong season endurance will surely win your acclaim!\nFilbert Brown Pearl Grey Cadet Blue\nCocoa Tan Covert Tan\ni J\nft* ott .-.I,","height":"21788","width":"14364"}}
